Nov 19 2009 	cheap with a deal as a place for a comfortable night's sleep but they clearly don't want you to spend time in the room	We stayed at the MGM grand for two nights in a celebrity Spa suite, following a half price offer on last minute. Checking in was easy until it came to finding our room - we had to ask five different staff for directions - the first four unsure of the layout and unable to help, and therefore spent the first 20 minutes wondering around a busy casino with heavy luggage. The celebrity spa suite comprised a large room, partly divided by a closet, with a desk, sofa and armchair in one half and a bed with bedside tables in the other. The closet contained a television. There was a sink and a fridge against one wall. Off of the room was a very large bathroom. The room was dark and even in the middle of the day needed all the lights on. The bed itself was clean, with good linen, and very comfortable, definitely the best part of the room. The bathroom was admittedly large with a large whirlpool mbath, but shabby with exposed pipes, and a shower which automatically flooded the floor. There was no tea or coffee in the room and a limited choice of channels, with no option for pay per view films. We understood that there was a spa, swimming pool and fitness suite but these all appeared to be at substantial additional cost and in no way clearly signposted. Our overall impression was that, unsurprisingly i suppose, they wanted to discourage you staying in your room, and that the MGM grand was wholeheartedly a casino first and hotel last (with none of the additional themes of some of the other hotels on the strip) and therefore i wouldn't recommend this hotel unless you get a really cheap deal and purely want a place to crash before heading back out.	
