Nov 6 2009 	All round good hotel	I have just returned from a trip to Las Vegas. We stayed at the MGM for 5 nights. Overall it is a good hotel. We opted for a Prima card which meant that we were upgraded to a bungalow suite. The room itself was nice and big and had two queen size beds which were fab, by far the most comfortable beds that I have slept on in a hotel. The facilities in the room were rubbish. There is no tea or coffee facilities and no fridge. We had 2 tv's but no fridge???? These are basic facilities and I can't understand why they were not in the room. We asked for some champagne glasses to be brought up and whilst the use of them was free, there was a delivery charge of around $3!!! Whilst the price is nominal, they cannot seriously charge for housekeeping to bring something to your room!!! Housekeeping were fine. They were a little late on a couple of days but not an issue as most of the time we were out of our room. The restaurants, bars etc in the hotel are fine. The prima card itself was good but there is a pressure to spend all of the resort credit. This is fine if you have regular meals etc but you are restricted to the MGM hotels (of which there is many! including the Bellagio, Mirage, Treasure Island). I would stay at the hotel again but next time I would probably like to be a bit more central, for example, Bellagio, Ceasars palace. I highly recommend seeing &quot;O&quot; at Bellagio. We booked our tickets online from the UK and we got 25%. Excellent show. In terms of clubs, the must go to clubs are: Monday -XS at the WynnTuesday - Pure at Ceasars PalaceWednesday - LAX at LuxorThursday - Tao at VenetianFriday - Tryst at WynnSaturday - any clubWe also took a helicopter flight over the canyon with sundance helicopters and that was fab. Just don't drink too much the night before!	
Nov 5 2009 	Nice room good location but tight slots	I just got back from staying at the MGM 10/29-11/1. Check-in was fast at ~1pm. They didn't have the king room I requested available at that time so I took 2 queens. Got a Grand Tower room on the 24th floor with a view of the airport &amp; mountains in the distance which was fine with me. The room was good sized, clean &amp; comfortable. My room was a comped based on my play at other MGM hotels &amp; my first stay here. I found the staff friendly, but the slots very tight &amp; the drink service not so great. They offer a fast continental Starbucks breakfast (fruit, pastry or muffin &amp; coffee) with guarantied delivery within 15 minutes up until 11am for just under $10 which beat waiting in the LONG morning Starbucks line. Other room service was fine, but expect to wait ~45 minutes which is about the same as other large Vegas hotels. The beds are very comfortable. The first night was nice &amp; quiet, but FRI &amp; SAT (Halloween weekend) was very loud. Friday night we were awaken ~ 3am with a fire alarm &amp; Saturday ~4:30 with loud partygoers which I am incline to write-off as just a rowdy Halloween crowd. This hotel seems to cater to the young rowdy crowd, but again, it could just be the Halloween weekend crowd. I have also stayed at Ballys, the Mirage, the Las Vegas Hilton, the Bellagio, the Wynn, the Stratosphere, and Circus Circus. The monorail is very convenient &amp; it was nice to stay once on the south end of the Strip. The hotel is not as nice as the Bellagio or the Wynn, but the room was more than adequate. I think this hotel is better suited for table players &amp; maybe families with children than a 40+ slot player. I would give this hotel one more try, but I didn't like it as well as Ballys, the Mirage, The Las Vegas Hilton, the Bellagio or the Wynn (all also comped rooms). If you can find a good priced deal then it is worth a try.	
Nov 5 2009 	Very Outdated	I stayed at MGM Grand for five nights as part of a business conference. I have been to Las Vegas many times and have stayed at several of the nicer hotels, and MGM Grand was my least favorite. If I were rating it solely based on the rooms, amenities, location and appearance, I would give it 2 stars. However, I am increasing it to 3 stars because the service was good.Rooms and GroundsI stayed in a room overlooking the airport, which was nice for me because I like plane spotting. Otherwise, it would have been a disturbance due to the noise from incoming helicopters and jets taking off (including fighter jets). The room itself was small compared to those at the other nicer Vegas resorts. There were no amenities in the room – no minibar, no robe, no slippers. The bathroom was dated and the bath/shower was comparable to a Motel 6. The bed was surprisingly comfortable. The lobby and grounds were outdated and in need of maintenance. The tiles in the lobby were cracked and dirty. Lobby flowers were fake (this is no Bellagio). Basically, it looks like the hotel hasn’t been renovated or refreshed in over 20 years.Hotel AmenitiesThe hotel pool was basic for a Vegas hotel. Since I was there for business, I didn’t have much pool time. The spa was quite nice as was the fitness facility (which was too small). There are only 2 or 3 stores in the complex and none offered anything interesting or of quality. I dined at both Craftsteak and Emeril’s. Craftsteak was fabulous, and I have written a separate review praising it. Emeril’s, in contrast, was standard tourist fare of an unimpressive nature. I do not gamble, so I can not comment on the merits of the casino.ServiceThe service at the hotel was good. We were greeted with a smile at reception and were assisted promptly and courteously. Room service was similarly good and the servers were friendly and helpful. In summary, there are much nicer resorts in Las Vegas in the same price range or just slightly higher. Bellagio, Mandalay Bay and Venetian are all remarkably nicer and would be preferable.	
