Nov 4 2009 	Glad i picked MGM for 1st trip to Vegas!	We had a 12 night stay at the MGM Grand 16 - 28 Oct 09 for our wedding/honeymoon. After hours of reading trip advisor reviews decided this sounded about the best hotel for us and i have to say we were very glad we picked this hotel! Apologies in advance if this is a long review, its my 1st ever review and im hoping to give an informative review for other 1st timers, (particularly those without bottomless pockets, like us !) I have put at the bottom a few things that hopefully will be useful in regard to hints/tips in case you dont want to read my whole essay!!!!We arrived about 8.30 pm on friday night (paid approx $15 dollars including tip from the airport by taxi - long taxi lines but moved quickly). There were no lines for check-in, we had pre-paid for our holiday and had a non-smoking king room booked but being a smoker i asked if there were any smoking rooms available, they only had 1 double queen room but having seen pictures on trip advisor i was happy to accept that. The check-in was quick and staff were polite. There was no queue for the lift (seperate lifts for different sections of floor levels) and there were no, or very small queues, during our entire stay.We had room 108 on floor 29 - We had a fantastic view of the mountains - the room was very large (and did not 'smell' like a smoking room!), 2 big beds to choose from, with a bedside cabinet, wardrobe (with a light in it), TV (in a cabinet with drawer/cupboard space and a safe), 2 comfy chairs and a table and a lounge type chair and 3 lamps (no ceiling lights) and some nice pictures on the walls. Nice large bathroom with shower over bath. The rooms were clean and in good condition (a few marks on the carpet near beds and on furniture - remember this is a hotel room and not everyone treats hotel rooms as they would their own home!)Loved the location at the top of the strip, we were within reach of all the strip attractions but at the &quot;quieter&quot; end. The monorail was about a 10 minute walk within the hotel &amp; there were a choice of nearby deuce bus stops within 10 mins walk also (we mainly got on outside the Tropicana as there were hardly ever any queues as opposed the large queues outside Hardrock Cafe area). The deuce bus is better value and has more stops than the monorail)The hotel is massive, as all the vegas hotels appeared to be (if you dont like walking then i guess vegas itself will be an issue!) There are lots of things to see/do within the hotel, plenty of places to eat from casual to fine dining. We visited Craftsteak once - nice staff but fairly expensive for the quality. We went to McDonalds, Nathan's hotdogs, the pizza bar and the chinese - all cheap and good (particularly the chinese), we also used starbucks - there are 2 or 3 in the hotel. We had breakfast at the buffet several times (about $16 each) lots of choice, very good value for the amount you can eat (we were stuffed nearly all day), service was good but be there early (or late) to avoid long lines, (the same at lunch &amp; dinner) - we paid for the all day buffet on our last day, again good value but lunch and dinner were very &quot;the same&quot; with just a few extras for dinner. I wouldnt pay for the lunch or dinner as separates as i dont think either would be particularly good value that way but great as an all day combinationWe went to MGM's Crazy Horse Paris show (1/2 price ticket vouchers in variety of booklets/ticks for tonight) - it was a very good show but not a &quot;vegas showgirl&quot; type production.We only managed to get 1 afternoon by the pool - all were very nice and the lazy river was fun - no problems getting a lounger but didnt see a single drink server all afternoon. We didnt try the wet republic area.There are plenty of shopping opportunities, Starlane Mall is easy to miss tho as not well signposted (it has the cheaper more vegas-ey types shopping so guess thats why its hidden away - its on the left of the main lobby exit at the side of the car rental area).There are several bars/clubs but we only went to the bar once in the main casino - mostly the bars seemed reasonably busy (more so at weekend).We aren't gamblers but we tried the slots - won a little but were mainly on the 1 cent slots for a little entertainment! Weekends the casino itself was very busy! (again as all the big casinos seemed to be).Thats about it for the hotel itself - I'll give a quick rundown of our general vegas trip and a will do a seperate review for the Chapel of the Flowers where we were married.We had a coach trip to the Grand Canyon - were originally decided to go to the west rim as its a little nearer and opportunities to up-grade to skywalk/helicopter/boat trips. We were persuaded that the south rim would be better as its 'more senic and colourful' - we had a VERY long day (picked up at 6.20am returning approx 9.30pm), the views along the way were great and we had a couple of stops, 1 10min stop at the back of the Hoover Dam (not allowed to stop at the front of it as not on a Hoover Dam tour!) - Dam itself looked amazing but would have been nice to have had longer there to have a quick walk over it and proper view), 1 15min coffee stop each way (nothing special just a garage/store) and a 45min lunch break at Grand Canyon Railway, lunch was very rushed with at least 3 coach loads arriving for a buffet lunch which if im honest was very low budget and didnt have much choice. The Grand Canyon itself is AMAZING - we got 1 hour stops at 2 different points - there were food/drink opportunities and souvenier shopping/tourist advice places at both stops, but that is it - in hindsight i wish we had stuck to our guns and done the west rim as an upgrade to helicopter and/or boat trip would have topped the trip off! Go to the West Rim!!!!! Trips to the west rim are a little bit more expensive but i think they include a bbq lunch with the indians there, plus its 3 hours nearer (giving more time to do upgrades) and there are the upgrades available if you want.Vegas itself involves LOTS of walking (or bus riding!) - there are tons of things to see and do, the hotels are all fabulous but all are designed to get you in to spend money and there are few opportunities to sit unless at a bar or slot machine. Huge range of shopping opportunities. The Deuce bus was $3 single trip, $7 for 24 hour unlimited trips &amp; $15 for 3 day unlimited )The Bellagio fountains (free) are ABSOLUTELY FANTASTIC!!! - A DEFINATE MUST SEE!!! try to see it at night!!!Bellagio Conservatory (free) - Smaller than expected but with nice displaysThe Mirage Volcano (free) - Great show, better than expected! Try to be near to feel the heat!The Sirens at TI (free - outside the front of main lobby) - Fabulous free show - about 20-30 mins - try to get in the middle walkway to the lobby itself so you get a good view of both sides - was packed every time we went past!MGM Lions (free) - just a couple of lions - mostly sleeping tho' (some cubs occasionaly in seperate section and chance to have pic with cub $25) - the tunnel to walk through is about 10 foot long! Honestly, - bit over-hyped!Flamingo Wildlife Habitat (free) - i'd heard they had penguins?!? - walked the entire place and saw flamingo, various ducks/swans, some terrapins and koi carp but NO penguins!!!Freemont Street - Downtown (free) - Very impressive light/music show at night - cheaper to eat/drink, casinos look a little more worn but generally a nice atmosphere all round - stay in the lit areas at night, the general downtown area is fairly rough and not a place to be walking around at night!!!Imperial Palace Car Collections - impressive collection of cars but make sure you use a 2 for 1 voucher not worth full price!Mandalay Bay Shark Reef (approx $20 each adult) - Massively over-hyped, just a sealife/blueplant type place with a 1 crocodile and 1 komodo dragon,1 large lizard - tho' there were 2 huge turtles in the main tank, definately didn't see the 30ft shark tho'!Stratosphere Tower (approx $15 each adult - more for rides as well) - Fantastic views all round - the rides looked terrifying!!!!Las Vegas Outlet Centre - Deuce bus goes there, worth a visit if you have time/like shopping, some good bargains to be had and plenty of food outlets.Definately check out the vouchers and coupons for attractions offers, tixs for tonight looked good value for a variety of shows/food offers (we used them once for tickets to Crazy Horse Show). Make sure you are stocked up with water - walgreens and 7-11's seem to be about the cheapest for water/coke etc - walgreens we also quite reasonable for vegas souveneirs!BEWARE the timeshare touts - they will get you in before you know where you are! You can get good (or better) deals on shows at tix for tonight and pick up the free slots vouchers they give you from the various booklets, without having to go through the whole timeshare thing!The &quot;girls for you&quot; ticketers are fairly annoying slapping their tickets and trying to hand them to anyone &amp; everyone (they seem to double in number at weekends!!!) but no problem ignoring them.We had a fantastic wedding/honeymoon/holiday and i hope my review will be of some use...HAVE FUN!!!!!!!!!!!!!!	
Nov 3 2009 	It doesn't get much better than this	stayed at the MGM October 25-27. Checked in at the registration desk at the airport at 8:30am, booked the roundtrip airport shuttle from them and was on my way. upon arrival at the hotel I went straight to my room. No need to stand in that line in the lobby. Was upgraded to a King Bungalow Suite. All I can say is ....WOW! the room was awesome. Huge bathroom, wet bar, mini-fridge, safe, king size bed on one side of the room with sitting area on the other divided by the entertainment center with swiveling tv. 2 HUGE floor to ceiling windows overlooked New York, New York and Excalibur. but the best part was the bed. the pillowtop mattress was incredible. The maid service was great, twice a day! the elevators are divided into different elevators for a range of floors. the elevator for my room, 14th floor, served floors 13-20, which was quite expedient.The pool area is quite large. would've liked to have seen the back lot river or whatever it is, but it's closed for the winter now. The available pool areas were more than adequate with bar and snack service nearby and towels provided.The food court was great and quite accessible. the monorail was awesome, even if it was a bit of a walk from the strip to most of the monorail stations.No need to stand in line to check out either. just fill out the express check-out card and leave it in the box near the elevators and you're done!Drink service was rather slow at the quarter slots, but then again, it's the quarter slots! Yes, the hotel is big. yes, there's smoking in the casino area. it's vegas, get over it!All in all, a great trip with a great hotel. i would definitely stay here again.	
