Oct 20 2009 	Customer Service is not their Specialty	I recently visited Las Vegas, Nevada in the United States. My fiancée and I chose to stay at the MGM Grand due to a special offer that made a Celebrity Spa Suite available to us.For the details, continue reading below, but in a nutshell…..Staying at the MGM is great if you do not ask for Customer Service. The beds are great, the casino is okay, and the hotel is respectably clean. However, if you need a bit of friendly service from the individuals that make up their staff then you might face a bit of trouble with their less-than-stellar &quot;customer service&quot;. Their blasé attitude gave me the impression that money talks, and it happens to be the only language they speak.The check-in to the room was quick and easy from the McCarran airport check-in desk. The room assignment was adequate for our purpose, however the view left much to be desired - overlooking the rooftop of the ground floor level. Hello HVAC units! To their credit, we were invited by the Front Desk to try in the morning for a better view, but I wasn’t about to spend time playing musical chairs when I was on vacation.The room was ample, about 40% larger than their baseline rooms. The furniture showed signs of wear, specifically the coffee table had a few scuff marks, the couch showed some wear, but all of it was in usable condition. Imagine a relative’s house – the furniture is not brand new, but it’s pretty comfy to sit on.The bed was a king-sized bed with a pillow-top mattress, 4 large king pillows, and a body pillow with the MGM logo. I daresay that the bed was the best part of the room. The 27” CRT television was nestled in a wardrobe that served as a divider between the bed and the sitting area.The casino is large but the impression is that it was not designed so well. The poker pit is overcrowded and small, even on a weekday; the table games are not very plentiful, and waitresses could use a day off. The addition of massage girls in the casino did not add to the impression of comfort, but actually caused me to think “seedy.”The personality of any particular dealer is a crapshoot, but I found that they are generally friendly since they don’t actually represent the casino but more themselves since they work for tips.The shopping area of the hotel is very pleasant. In this area you can find restaurants, shopping and some entertainment, as well as the Monorail that travels between hotels in Las Vegas. The ceilings are high, the area is clean, and it all leads to MGM’s pool area, which, unfortunately we did not get to visit. Though we understand Mandalay Bay’s pool area is the best on the Strip, by far.We dined at Shibuya, and took in a Cirque du Soleil show, Ka.We also left an item behind and that experience was just awful. After calling and telling them exactly where the item was left, their security calls back to report that the item was not recovered. So, I can only conclude that the people employed at the MGM Grand are not only not interested in taking care of you during your stay, but some of them are willing to steal from you when they can.Overall, this hotel struck me as just that. A hotel. It's just a place to stay.Nothing spectacular, and certainly nothing better than any of the other hotels on the Strip. The indifference that I experienced only makes me wonder what sort of business ethic the MGM Grand employs. Since they are so large, perhaps they trivialize the people who stay there, and like an assembly line, everyone gets the same old standard service. It’s too bad their standard service is sub-par.All the beds on the Strip are nice. Thank you MGM, for encouraging me to try out other hotels on my next trip to Las Vegas.	
Oct 20 2009 	Best Value on the Strip! Size is exagerated...	I stayed here last week with my girlfriend on our first trip to Las Vegas... I'll start by saying that many people exagerate the size of this place. Yes it's big for a hotel, but not big for a place in Las Vegas. I've worked in larger offices. You'll only find it big here if you're the type that drives one block to the corner store.Location... It's at the South end of the strip, but a 15 minute walk to Paris and Belllagio, which it makes it great IMO. Our travelling friends stayed at the Encore hotel, and we much preferred the MGM location. The South end of the strip feels much cleanerm safer and livelier than the North-end. Enjoy exploring MGM, Tropicana, NYNY, Exalibur and take the free monorail to Luxor and Mandalay Bay (tip: try Burger bar for great burgers and Beligian bews!). The monorail stop is a short walk from the Grand Tower rooms, and very handy for returning after a night elsewhere on the strip.Checkin/out: Slow...no other word for it. Checkin at the airport if you can, and request a room in the grand tower (don't let them give you west wing), near the elevator. If it's your first time in Vegas, try asking for a strip view room too - we got one. Be patient... I'm not sure why they're so slow. Use the Express Checkout if you can.The Room: We asked for a room with a King bed, but accepted one with two Queens..we're not big people. Room was neatly decorated, very spacious with a great view of City Center, Bellagio, PH and Monte Carlo. The beds were super-soft - some of the most comfy hotel beds I've ever slept on...lots of fluffy pillows too. Bathroom was equally modern and very spacious with a decent shower and bath. Everything seemed very clean, though I did notice more dirt under the beds when I was looking around before we left - normal I guess. Lots of towels and very nice shampoo/conditioner. Nothing terribly special - but a good quality hotel room. Inside our room was always very quiet - we never heard a peep from outside or a neighbouring room.The Pool - The first thing I did was hit the pool. It's a 5-10 minute walk from your room (don't believe any of the 20 minute stories you've heard), and a huge area. Most people just seem to sit around and look good - except on the backlot river, which is a lot of fun, but certianly not the only good pool. Lots of 20-30 somethings playing around the river drunk (we fit right in), and people of all ages sunbathing around the other pools.The Restaurants - we ate at L'Atelier Joel Robouchon, for their $39 L'Unique meal - great value for fine dining and enough to fill us up. They also have some of the best bread I've ever had, and the only good bread I had in Vegas. There are too many other great restaurants to discuss - pick a good one and try it.The Atmosphere - MGM has a young, hip atmosphere. You'll see lots of very well dressed 20-30 somethings ready to head for a night on the town. At the same time, you'll see people from every generation enjoying one of the best value resorts in Vegas. It's a great mix.As an aside, we visited two of our friends who were staying in a mini-suite at the Encore (a 5 star hotel), and I would have taken the MGM over the Encore for the same price. The suite was nothing special, and the MGM's location and nearby restaurants attractions beat the Encore's big time.	
Oct 20 2009 	MGM is Grand so much to do and see!	My husband and I just returned from a 5 night stay at the MGM. Last time we stayed at the Excalibur, which was terrible. The MGM has so much to offer. Our room was in the Grand Tower, which had originally booked. But be careful when you check in, they will try and move you over to the West Wing. Stand firm on your Grand Tower reservation. The room was very big, bed was so comfortable, big bathroom and lovely view. We rented a mini fridge for $35.00 for the whole stay (well worth it), and I brought a little coffee maker (which I paid $20.00 for), therefore we had coffee and drinks available in our room. The walk down to get coffee from Starbucks, etc. is a bit a a ways. The pools are excellent, Wolfgang Puck restaurant is top notch. Another restaurant to try when you are in Vegas is the Mesa Grill at Ceasars Palace. The MGM casinos are very clean and they shampoo the carpets every night. Air is fresh and drink offerings are plentiful.	
Oct 19 2009	What I think of Vegas	I just got home from a 4 night trip to Vegas. (Oct. 19 2009) We stayed at the MGM Grand Hotel and Casino. When we first got there it was so exciting checking into our hotel. Everything was extravegant, until we got to our room. First off, we got the wrong room (we requested a king bed and got 2 queen's). We couldn't change until the next day. The room wasn't as great as I had expected. It appeared to be an outdated luxurious room. Don't get me wrong it wasn't like a ghetto motel, we still had a pilowtop mattress with a comfy duvet. However it was older looking. It was also a smoking room which tend to age quicker than non-smoking. We then requested to change to an upgraded room. We were able to view a king bed room in the west wing (the new side). This was very nice however the bathroom was open concept and smaller. So we went back to the grand tower with a king. Later that day we had no hot water and conceirge didn't seem to help much rather than send in a request for maintenece which had no time line. Luckily it went back on shortly after. Overall MGM was great. It had an awesome pool area. Lots of partiers. Not the place if you are looking for a luxurious posh setting.Bellagio was beautiful. The fountains were really cool. Def posh!! Ceasars was amazing and seemed more civilized. Mirage was really cool. Volcano outside is amazing. MGM is a far walk to Bellagio/Ceasars/Forum Shops etc. It took 30-45mins from our room to Bellagio. Minimal croos-walks was annoying. The one thing that drove me nuts were all the Latinos standing on the street handing out flyers to adult entertainment industry business' a.k.a porn/strip clubs/hookers/night clubs. They don't just hand them out they smack the cards on there hands making a horrible clapping noise followed by shoving the cards in your face. I was with my boyfriend and they didn't care. They try to dump them on anyone...singles, couples, families..I was really getting irritaded with that. The strip is covered in these cards which made the city seem dirtier.Overall it was definately an exciting place to be. If I go again I still would go to MGM especially for the pool and Wet Republic. Otherwise I'd go to Ceasar's Palace or Mirage. Venetian I didn't go into, but looked really cool from the outside. Definitely want to go back again!!	
Oct 19 2009 	Great hotel BUT check your hotel billing as often as possible	I will echo most of the other rave reviews and simply say that for the $63(plus tax) a night I paid for a regular room on the 21st floor, everything was very nice. The room, check in and check out, the buffet - all were above average. BUT I did want to alert those of you that charge things to your room to be very careful. Based on an experience I had, I am warning you check your hotel charges in detail before you leave. Here is my story: We ate at the Rainforest Cafe on October 15th and checked out on the 16th. Only because my family was slow in coming down to the lobby, I sat and reviewed my bill. I noticed the Rainforest Cafe(restaurant at the South end of the hotel) charged me twice for the same amount on the same day. Two charges of $94 with the same &quot;charge code&quot; (the number that appeared on my hotel bill). I won't bore you with all the details but the restaurant admitted the error and corrected the charges. Although I was only briefly inconvenienced(the walk from the lobby to the restaurant and back to the lobby is a killer) and the bill was fixed, I am still not convinced it was just an &quot;innocent mistake.&quot; Then again, charging you twice for the same meal probably wouldn't be the smartest way to rip someone off in a city that prides itself in ripping people off. So guess I'll go with the one time error explanation. So in summary, the hotel is great but be sure to keep an eye on what you charge to your room. I suggest you get a billing summary at the end of each night you stay, especially because I had to fight the check out lines twice-once to get the erroneous bill and again to get a hard-copy of the corrected bill since the restaurant does not give you one.	
