Oct 15 2009	MGM - A Great Experience!	Met my sister &amp; her husband in Vegas for our annual &quot;vacation&quot; from Sept. 26 to Oct. 2. We were very torn on where to stay this trip. We usually stay at Luxor but since they've changed the casino &amp; pool areas, to us it's lost that &quot;loving feeling&quot;. So we had a choice between Mandalay Bay &amp; MGM and picked MGM. I must say I was a bit nervous about staying there after reading some of the reviews here. But my nervousness and fears were for nothing because we had a wonderful stay! Yes the hotel is huge and requires a lot of walking- it's VEGAS!! After a day or two you tend to learn the short cuts from getting from point A to point B. Thanks to the reviews though I did tell my sister that we should request Grand Tower rooms and not the West Wing rooms, which we did and I'm extremely pleased with doing so. The Grand Tower room I was in had a King sized bed that was the most comfortable bed I have ever slept on. I mean SERIOUSLY it was so comfortable that not once did I wake up during the night nor did I have any backaches and only once did I wake up with a headache. The room was clean and the view was of New York New York, Excalibur, Luxor etc. It was awesome! Room was 24th Floor Room 314- I think. Bathroom was huge and even though it showed signs of age it was clean and bright. I loved that it had an in-room safe that was under the TV and large enough to hold my mini laptop, ipod, jewelery and many other things. We went to the pool 2 days and both times had no problem getting chaises. We didn't get there early, around 11am and it wasn't crowded at all. The music wasn't terribly loud but we did stay away from Wet Republic so we could lay out in peace. Drink servers around the pool were scarce but the bar was right there so it was no skin off our noses to just get up and order something. Loved the Lemon Kiss and would recommend that drink to anyone who likes lemonade (with alcohol of course, lol!). Very refreshing! The bar attendants let my sister and her husband have little tastes of each of their frozen drinks so they could find the flavor they liked- very cool of them I think.We ate at the buffet for most breakfasts and some dinners because we had a 2 for 1 on our hotel offer. Since it was only myself in my party I was given 1/2 off- you do have to charge to your room and then it is adjusted. Food at the buffet was the same every day but it was good and filling and we had no complaints at all.Now Las Vegas hotels (on Strip) do not have coffee makers in the rooms any longer. I was told a few years ago that it was some fire code thing but I'm pretty sure it's so you have to either order coffee from room service or go down into the casino to the coffee stands. So with that said and me being a total morning coffee freak I simply called down to room service every morning and ordered. Yes it was $6 for a small pot or $9 for a larger pot but hey it saved me from having to get dressed, go downstairs, stand in line and then end up paying $5+ for a coffee. I'd call down, order, they'd say 25 mins. but within 15 mins. someone was knocking at my door and placing a fresh, hot and yummy pot of coffee on the table in my room- PERFECT!!! It was actually something I looked forward to every morning while waiting for my sister and her husband to get ready for breakfast.Now the morning I woke up with a terrible headache- after breakfast my sister said they were going to lay by the pool, I said I was going to see if I could get in for a massage. Again we had 25% off spa services so I thought I'd see if I could take advantage of that. It was 12:25pm when I got to my room, called the spa and asked if they had any opening for a hot stone massage. Yes Ms. Tucker- how soon would you like to get in? We have a 1pm opening! Bing bang boom! Just like that I was booked and heading down for the most relaxing massage. It did the trick and my headache vanished. The spa itself is beautiful and relaxing. They have these big, comfy lounger chairs to sit in while waiting to be called for your treatment. The casino is large, very large actually but there is something for everyone there. I couldn't believe how packed all the tables, roulette and craps tables were. If there is a recession going on you sure couldn't tell it from looking at those. I actually found $1 video roulette and being a bit skeptical sat down to play. I liked it better than the real thing since now even for &quot;cheap&quot; roulette at Orleans or Gold Coast they have change the betting. $5 minimum but if you play anything outside it is $5 on each spot or you can split $5 on the numbers. With video roulette I could play $1 if I wanted or as much as I desired. I played $3 per spin and everytime I played I walked away with a profit! OK so to wrap this up on our last night there we decided to go see MGM Crazy Horse show- which I have written a review on. It was wonderful and actually a show that I'm looking forward to seeing again next year. It's French burlesque with funky lighting and extremely hot girls! Loved every minute of it but will warn you that if you are looking for a &quot;Vegas Show Girl&quot; type of show, this isn't it- go see Jubilee instead. I also saw Bite at the Strastophere the 2nd day I was there and it's a decent show. Get the 2 for 1 tickets because it's worth $25 per person, not sure it's worth $49.95 per person. Sexy, erotic vampire story set to rock 80's music and I was digging the music!! Don't believe it when they say they take members from the audience- they are dancers and singers planted in the audience but it was fun overall. OK so to sum it up- MGM was GRAND and it's huge so if you don't like &quot;walking&quot; then don't stay here. Grand Tower rooms are very nice, buffet is pretty darn good and thank you to the morning room service servers! Oh and thank you to the floor manager who promptly tried to fix my TV issue and when he couldn't called maintenance for me who was there within 20 mins. Everyone from the front desk check-in to the maids who smiled and said Good Morning to me every morning when I headed out and they were just getting ready to start their day were absolutely wonderful. I didn't meet one staff member there who was rude or made you feel like you weren't welcomed. Check out was done on the TV and didn't even have to go to the front desk. Called the Bell Desk who came and got my suitcases for me and held them until I was ready to head to the airport.I'd definately recommend the MGM Grand to anyone going to Vegas! I'd also tell them to watch the different websites and offers because we got ours for $55 a night and it was money well spent! Enjoy!!!	
Oct 14 2009 	MGM Grand has it all	My husband and I stayed at the MGM Grand from Saturday, October 10th to Tuesday, October 13th for my husband's birthday. This was my first trip to Vegas, my husband, on the other hand, felt like he was returning home. A Southern California native, he has been to Vegas about 60 times, mostly staying at the MGM. I, on the other hand, was making my debut visit to Sin City.Just so you know, my husband and I are 30. We like to gamble, eat, and drink, and not necessarily in that order. We didn't go to any shows, so I can't speak to that side of Vegas.Here we go: My husband is a member of the Players Club, so our rooms were already discounted and we were upgraded to a suite upon check-in (a welcome surprise after a 5 1/2 hour flight from New York City). The suite was nice. A little dated, but still very nice to have the extra space. The beds were extremely comfortable. After checking-in, we went to Wolfgang Puck's to split a pizza and grab a drink. Good food and I though reasonably priced. I'm used to NYC prices, so I really didn't find Vegas to be all that overwhelming. The pizza was really good and more than enough for two to share for lunch. We played some paigow at the MGM, then explored the hotel--so much to see! Lovely collection of restaurants in the hotel, with lots of variety. The restaurants all are having deals and lots of happy hours, which I'm told was a sign of the tough economic times.That evening, we went to the NY NY and Monte Carlo to gamble. I liked the Monte Carlo, but found it to be a bit too brightly lit. One of the drunk guys at our paigow table actually managed to light it on fire while lighting his cigarette, so that provided some excitement.When we returned to our room, we were pleased to see room service had delivered a bottle of champagne and cake to our room for my husband's birthday. A totally unexpected surprise! Sunday, I laid out by the pool while my husband played poker. The pool was nice--very big, with lots of room and available chairs. That afternoon, we went to the Paris hotel and Bellagio. The champagne they serve you while playing at the Bellagio is awesome. That evening, we went to Craftsteak to celebrate my husband's birthday. I was extremely disappointed in Craftsteak. The lobster bisque was fabulous, but that is about it. We ordered the porterhouse for two and it was tough and honestly, a bit bland. I don't know if it was a one-off deal or what, but it was very disappointing. Monday, again, my husband played poker while I went to the outlet mall. We met up later in the afternoon to go see the Venetian and Caesars Palace. The Venetian was beautiful. Caesars was big, huge, glamorous, but I really liked the Venetian. By that evening, I was exhausted. Too much of a good thing, I guess. Vegas is like no other city in the world. My debut trip was a success (even though we lost!), and I look forward to my next trip to Vegas and the MGM Grand.	
