Oct 13 2009 	MGM Grand Las Vegas - Nevada	My hubbie &amp; I are seasoned travellers. We stayed at the MGM Grand Las Vegas for our first wedding anniversary we had previously stayed at NYNY for our honeymoon last year. We arrived on the 16/9/9 for one week, the hotel was very busy due to the Mayweather fight. Check in was fast, efficient, we had booked online and got a special offer with lastminute.com which worked out £200 cheaper than booking directly with the hotel. We stayed in the West Wing and after reading some of the reviews on this site I was stressed out to the HILT!!! Our room had a large king/queen double bed, with a window overlooking it. The view from this window was fine, we could see NY NY. The room has all that anyone could need, plenty of plus, a chair, desk, bedside lights which are very nicely designed. The wardrobe space is plentiful and there is an in room safe as well. The room is very well designed, lots of mirrors, glass and a very stylish swivel chair. The bathroom is fantastic, yes it has a frosted glass door as does the shower but this was not an issue for me &amp; hubbie and I can’t see how it would be an issue unless you are very prudish. The shower is brill, more like a wet room, very spacious and lots of lovely hot water. The pressure is great also, we had toiletries and towels which were replenished every day. Our room was also cleaned every day without having to ask. The hotel itself is HUGE but after a day or two you get used to it, there are loads of restaurants, cafes, a few bars and nightclubs. We ate at Pearl Chinese which was a fantastic meal, and very reasonable. We also ate in a steakhouse Fiamma Trateorri, which was fairly expensive but great quality. We also tried Diego Mexican but I thought it was over rated. I would recommend the deli next door to the sports book for a quick bagel and a cup of tea/coffee in the morning. The lion’s den is impressive but we had seen it last year so was not fazed by it. All the staff we encountered were courteous and professional. The best thing about this hotel is the pools - there are 6 of them I think. The best one is the lazy pool - this is simply the best. The pool has a current which guides you around the whole length of the pool, you also encounter waterfalls on your journey. This is a place for everyone families, couples everyone. I liked that the pool was not pretentious and everyone was just there for a good time. As for Las Vegas - what can I say I love it!! The sun is just great, as is the atmosphere. We are already planning our next trip. I can recommend Planet Hollywood for shops, it has a victorias secret which came in handy! also the Tropicana restaurant/bar is great we had a fantastic meal there. Also fab for was dennys,hard rock cafe. We got the deuce a few times which was ok but very packed. The monorail which runs between mgm to Mandalay Bay is much better and I think there is another mono rail which goes in the other direction. We visited most hotels I was very impressed with the Mandalay Bay - went there to see the Killers which were AMAZING. We ate there at Red White and Blue and it was very cheap but very nice food and friendly staff. Also liked Caesars, NY NY, Wynn, Palazzo. Didn’t like Flamingo, Harrahs, or Venetian - the reviews are right the smell is very overpowering!!. We went down to Bill's Gamblin Saloon which was just fab, there was even an Elvis impersonator - what more could you ask for!! Plus the machines seemed to pay out well here, and older hotels such as Circus Circus, Riviera etc. 2 small gripes about LV I don’t like the smoking - but hey this is sin city &amp; I just held my breath!! Also the ticket guys who hand out 'hot girls' cards - very annoying &amp; invade your personal space... also means there is a lot of rubbish about. Anyways I could talk all day about LV - enjoy if you are heading there enjoy !!!!* From last years trip also would recommend going to see the Cirque de Solei - Love show (beatles) and Steve Wyrick - very entertaining.	
Oct 13 2009 	Great Stay - But Don't Stay in the West Wing!	The MGM is great! My husband and I booked our trip on a web site that gave us our airfare and our hotel room in a package. When we checked in at the airport (which I advise!) we requested a king bed instead of 2 queens. The guy said that they had one in their West Wing. My husband and I didn't know what the &quot;West Wing&quot; was so we said okay. Let me tell you that the West Wing is a hole!!! Seriously...there is no lighting, no privacy and it's about a quarter of a mile down a long hallway. You automatically know that you've entered the &quot;West Wing&quot; when the lighting even in the hallway gets ridiculously dark! The lighting in the so-called “bathroom” is also a joke. Even if you put your face up to the mirror you still can’t put your makeup on. We stayed the one night in the room and immediately went to the front desk the next morning to request a move. The guy behind the counter was more than helpful to move us and even gave us a King room with a great view of half the strip. He was so great! So the hotel is fabulous and great access to the strip but just stay clear of the West Wing! Stay in the Grand Tower...they are great rooms!	
Oct 13 2009 	Fantastic Hotel for a weekend break in Las vegas	We stayed at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas in Oct 09, and were pleasantly surprised by how efficiently run the hotel was, considering its size and quantity of rooms. The check in at the airport MGM desk was easy, we were brought to the hotel by a passenger van, and were so delighted with our lovely room on the 19th floor with a fab strip view. It was a deluxe king room and for the money, was fantastic value. The Bathroom was huge and the room was super clean. The overall service was really good and check out was just as smooth as entering the hotel. I really do recommend this hotel, and having seen all the other hotels there, i am so pleased we stayed there. Not as flash as the Venetian or Bellagio, but not cheap like the New York or others on the strip.	
Oct 13 2009 	The West Wing is horrible!	Despite the Hotel's claims, the rooms that are available in the West Wing are, in the opinion of this paying customer, far from an upgrade and are not worth the extra money charged. To start, access to the West Wing rooms require that you walk, what seems like the length of the massive hotel to the every back, passing along the way, the main elevators to all of the other guest rooms, the casino floor, employee entrance areas and closets to a back hallway. The back hallway has a lower ceiling, horrible lighting, dark walls and an ugly industrial greyish blue/green/brown carpet that would be perfect to hide stains. At the end of this hallway are the elevators to the West Wing that are unlike any elevators in the entire Hotel. They resemble service elevators in need of a paint job as they are marred with scuff marks and lack any aesthetic appeal. The upper hallways of the West Wing are no different and have the same low ceiling, bad lighting, dark walls and ugly carpet. Once you enter the room, you will first realize that you do not have an enclosed bathroom. The bathroom sink is the first thing you see followed by two frosted glass enclosed stalls each with a shower and a toilet. Using the facilities had the feel and charm of using a public bathroom stall or showering at the local gym. The shower stall did not have a towel rack on the inside and required that you step out of the shower into the entrance foyer to get the towel. The room was small and not comfortable. It had one window over the bed that was smaller than most hotel windows. The view was nonexistent. The carpeting was the same industrial ugly greyish blue/green/brown carpet used in the hallway. There was nothing appealing about this hotel room unless you consider a flat screen T.V. and a Boise radio as an upgrade. Worst of all, as paying customer, management did nothing to address my dissatisfaction. Based on my experiences, I would not recommend staying at the MGM Grand. FDP.	
Oct 12 2009 	Great deal on a good hotel that caters to younger people.	We stayed at the MGM Grand from the 27th of September to the 1st of October. We had the 59 dollar a night rate which included 3 buffets each daily for my wife and I. We got there on a Sunday morning at 0900 and were told our room would be ready in an hour. We were given the room key cards and a phone number to call to find out the room number. Front desk and concerierge were never a problem during our stay. Short waits and helpful personnel. Our room (11-322) was clean, large and nice. It faced New York New York and we could see Excalibur, Luxor and Mandalay Bay. Pictures turn out incredibly detailed because there is so little humidity in the air. The buffet was good and we never waited more than 10 minutes in a line. Normally there was just a one to two minute wait until we were led to a table. The server was always at hand to get drink orders. The breakfast buffet is very good--especially when it's free. The lunch and dinner buffets are actually identical--they serve the same things. There was always something good to make a meal out of. The prime rib is sliced mercilessly thin and was pretty much a waste of time. The crab legs and peel-and-eat shrimp are presided over by a employee in a chef's hat--they dole out 3-4 small crab legs and maybe a half dozen shrimp at a time. Seemed kind of cheap. But there were many kinds of entrees that were very good and overall the buffet experience was worthwhile. The hotel is huge, but we found that we could cut hundreds of feet and a few minutes out of any trip by avoiding the carpeted pathway through the casino. Stick to the walls or pick a landmark in the direction you want and head directly towards it. Wear good walking shoes everywhere. The pool complex is fantastic--very nice and clean and plenty of towels available. The Backlot River (Lazy River) was supposed to be open only on the weekends per the hotel website, but we found that it was open every day of our stay. Our stay entitled us to 2 inner tube rentals. The tubes stick out a foot above the water and my wife (five foot two) found she was unable to touch bottom when she was on the tube. So she did not like them because she was unable to navigate. We found the slot machines at the casino to be unrelentingly tight. Cocktail waitresses are very few and far between. It was that way everywhere on the Strip and Downtown. We saw KA (buy one get one free with Players Club Card) and it was worthwhile. We bought 3 day passes for the MonoRail and it was worth the money. It was easy to take the MonoRail out from the MGM and walk back. It is true the MonoRail stations can be pretty far from the strip. At the MGM they are on the way to the pool. For the last two nights of our stay, we upgraded (30 dollars) to a Celebrity Spa Suite (room 25-339) which was pretty much as far away from the elevator that we could get. The suite had a huge bathroom with a whirlpool tub. All marble--really nice. The suite faced east down Tropicana and the airport. I don't know why but I liked this view better than the partial strip view. We found that the other reviewers comments about MGM catering to a younger crowd are true. The average guest seemed to be between 22-32 years old, and there were a lot of 4 man groups of twenty-somethings wandering aroud. We did not have any trouble with drunks yelling in the hallways.All in all, we've now stayed at the MGM and don't necessarily have to do so again. Being older, we'll probably move up to Bellagio or Caesar's Palace when the right deal comes along. But we had no problems with the MGM Grand and had a very good stay.	
