Oct 10 2009 	We got a great rate but this hotel lacks a pizzaz	Our room at the MGM was enormous and we had a good view across to New York, New York, Excalibur, The Luxor and Mandalay Bay but given this was a city of bright lights and countless entertainments, the MGM itself was a little dull. Staff were helpful but perhaps a little over formal and the sheer scale of the building never rewarded you with short cuts once you'd got yourself orientated - the pool was frustratingly far away and through the restaurant arcade and a short cut could easily have been added from the basement shopping arcade off of the main lobby and beneath valet parking. That said, we got an excellent deal on the room and our beds (2 queens bigger than anything you'd get here in London) were really comfortable. At present, a central strip hotel would be nicer given that the work around the new development next to the Monte Carlo makes the south strip feel a little isolated from Bellagio / Caesars Palace / Venetian etc etc but there's not much the MGM can do about that. The only other thing that the MGM could have done with were some $5 blackjack tables...at least during the day...or better guides as to how to play the more obscure games. We sampled both the buffet and the grand wok restaurants and both were good, offering high quality food at good value for money which seemed rare on the strip. We paid $59 a night with no resort fee on an offer and at that price the MGM is a great bet.	
Oct 10 2009 	West Wing hotel - good in theory not so much in execution...	Let me start off by saying that we booked our trip through Expedia for a king size bedroom at MGM Grand. The deal was crazy good with airfare, show tickets and ground transportation. And, I stayed with another party at MGM Grand about 3 years ago in the regular rooms so my experience with this room is compared to that experience. When we arrived at MGM Grand (it was a Wednesday night keep in mind), we were offered a r(regular) oom with 2 queen size beds in the hotel or a room with a king size bed in their 'new' West WIng. The West WIng was billed to us as similar to a New York effiency style apartment. Since it was our anniversary, we elected to take the West Wing room. First of all, if you enter and exit through the main casino, it takes even longer to get to this room because you exit the elevators and have to walk down a wing and then the West Wing hotel starts - carpet differs, that's how you know. Luckily, our room was close to the regular wing of the hotel. My husband found that the West Wing does indeed have it's own elevators and it takes you directly outside of the West Wing bar (which no one was really ever in -even late at night) and if you take that exit out you are on the side street beside the MGM Grand and nearest some of the tourist buses. That whole area sticks by the way, but after about a day, we figured this was the easiest way to get in and out of the building. The room - It is small, they did not lie to us about that , however I really would have appreciated some structure around the bathroom. The bathroom has a water closet, a shower and a vanity area. The shower and water closet have frosted glass around them and only that - no privacy and no way to masks any sounds if you need some potty time. Luckily, there is a TV built into the mirror in the bath area and you could turn that up full blast while you do your business. There is a TV directly on the other side of the wall which in my opinion took up too much space with the built in since you would think the newest part of this hotel would have flat screens. Nope. Probably sucks up a ton of energy too, but it's Vegas, right? All in all, th bed was nice, the desk and side chair/table was nice. The room is modern, but that is our style so we did like that. I do understand that in Vegas people do not spend a lot of time in their rooms, but we specifically stayed here so we would enjoy the time we did. I cannot say that I am impressed enough to return to MGM Grand. I would at least say no to the West Wing if I did. My other issue with MGM Grand is Wi-Fi is $15/day. That is riduculous for a hotel of this size. I stay for business at Hilton Garden Inn and Courtyard by Marriot all over the country and never pay for Wi-Fi. I wish I would have known this beforehand and I wouldn't have brought the laptop, jus used my iphone. We didn't win big in Vegas, but we didn't win big with our hotel choice either.	
Oct 10 2009 	Would recommend but not at the rack rate!	We stayed at MGM Grand for 4 nights in September. As advertised, it is a very large hotel and easy to get lost in. As commented on in other posts, this hotel does seem to cater to the young, the beautiful and the very drunk. Check in was reasonably quick and courteous, although the check in area is quite disorganised with guests forming their own queue’s. Other large hotels on the strip were better organised with an airport like set up for check in which meant that the first there was the first to check in. At MGM it is just a lucky dip as to who gets served first.Our Grand Tower room was a reasonable size with two fantastically comfortable queen sized beds (the best I have ever slept in!) and a nice bathroom. Requests for extra towels were dealt with promptly. We asked for a “high floor” non-smoking room and got the 28th floor. Our view was to the rear of the property and airport but still quite nice. Our friend got a smoking room on the 23rd floor with a fantastic strip view. The smoking room absolutely reeked of smoke even before she lit up for the first time. Our room on the 28th floor was reasonably quiet, although we were up the end of the hallway and there didn’t seem to be too many rooms filled around us. On the other hand, the room on the 23rd floor was near the lifts (as requested) which meant that many drunks were passing by at all hours. It also had an adjoining door which meant the noise from the neighbours was quite loud.The MGM Grand is located at the South end of the strip and has easy access to Tropicana, Excalibur, NYNY, Luxor and Mandalay Bay. If you are spending more than a few nights in Vegas I would recommend spending half your time at the “centre” strip and the other half at the south end. We spent 6 nights at Bills Gamblin Hall &amp; Saloon prior to the MGM and had a ball there.Eating and (particularly) drinking at the MGM Grand is not cheap, although there is a food court to get cheaper eats. You may be lucky enough to get “free” cocktails while playing the slots, however they take forever to arrive. Tipping the cocktail waitresses well did not seem to help.There did not seem to be much “winning” going on in the slots department, however I was lucky enough to win a good sized jackpot. For all of you Australian’s reading this, you need to be aware that any winnings on slot machines greater than $US1200 are taxed at 30%!!!! I was told that the tax could be claimed back in Australia but this is not the case. Of course it is not the casino’s fault, but quite disappointing all the same. If you do plan to spend cash gambling at MGM or other affiliated properties (Bellagio, Mandalay, Mirage, Treasure Island, NYNY, Luxor, Excalibur), I recommend joining the players club. This allows you to accrue points towards accommodation, meals, etc. I managed to get 3 all day buffets, 2 breakfast buffets, a meal on room service and one nights free accommodation with my accrued points. The buffet was acceptable, but not too much choice compared to others. However I can’t really complain as I did not pay.Overall, I think the MGM Grand is an okay place to stay providing you don’t pay the rack rate. At full price I think there are better offerings on the strip. If you are looking for a less expensive option in the best location on the strip, you can’t go past Bills Gamblin Hall and Saloon (see my review!)A final bit of advice – don’t forget your walking shoes!!!	
