Sep 18 2009 	Disappointing Service! From the perspective of a hotel manager.	Our trip was booked through US Airways Vacations because we had found a great deal on their website. Four couples in four rooms but on separate flights. Two couples arrived earlier in the day. We arrived at MGM on Saturday, September 12th 2009 around 2:00pm. The bell staff unloaded our luggage from the taxi and gave us a claim ticket to use once we reached our room. We were instructed to go inside toward the large video screen to check-in with the front desk staff. There are at least ten or more people working the massive desk (not including the concierge staff). The lobby has no ropes or lines guiding the continuous groups of people checking in or who are in need of assistance so everyone just gathers in a disorganized cluster to await assistance. Once we finally reached the desk we gave a young lady named Jennifer our names. After about 10 minutes of searching for our rooms Jennifer informed us that our reservation had been canceled on August 8th by US Airways. This was incorrect because the reservation was confirmed on that date. Jennifer also let us know that we would be able to stay at MGM but because it was Saturday we would have to pay high rack rate…$699.00 per night. This of course infuriated me and the others in my party. Unfortunately I had left my confirmation on my kitchen counter in the rush to get to the airport for departure early that morning. I asked where the business center was so that I could print the confirmation from my email. The business center is located just off the lobby. Be aware that it is not complimentary and it costs $5.00+ to use the internet. To date I have two charges on my bank account from LogicLink which is MGM’s business center. One is for $19.50 and one is for $15.00, I only used the business center the one time. We returned to the “line” in front of Jennifer as she instructed since she knew the situation. After waiting 30 minutes, because another couple ahead of us was having a problem, I gave Jennifer our confirmation from US Airways. It took just a moment to miraculously find our reservation. Our names had ALL been misspelled by whatever employee at MGM entered the information from US Airways Vacations. I’m still confused as to how Jennifer found by name a cancelled reservation but not the confirmed reservation. By this time one of our traveling companions had made the walk to the front desk from the pool to offer assistance. They had arrived earlier in the day and confirmed our reservations while they were checking in. They had also paid for an upgraded West Wing room versus a Grand Tower room which was the room type for our package. Because of the trouble with finding our reservation, Jennifer offered to upgrade the final two rooms to the West Wing and added a free meal at the Grand Buffet. I felt this was a nice gesture and was ready to forget the whole incident. I had called on September 1st to request a room on an upper floor with a Strip view. (So how did the person I spoke with at that time find our reservation if it was canceled on August 8th?) Jennifer did tell us that our new room was on a lower floor so the view wouldn’t be as good. I was ok with having a lesser view for the better room. The West Wing is quite a walk from the front desk and you are not escorted by a bellman so if you are unfamiliar with the hotel it can be quite challenging, especially after a frenzied check-in that leaves you somewhat discombobulated. Once we arrived at our room located on the 2nd floor I immediately began to wonder what about the room was an upgrade. The room was no larger than a Grand Tower room although it did have a more modern bathroom which included a walk in glass shower. The glass door to the water closet/toilet does not have a lock which is unnerving if anyone other than your spouse is in your room. I then opened the window to see our view. It was literally of a cement wall, a loading dock and a dumpster. Although Jennifer informed us the view wouldn’t be as good she should have explicitly told us that it would be NO view and I would have stayed in the Grand Tower room. Immediately I called the front desk to find out if another room was available on an upper floor. At this point Rachel answered the call and I explained the situation. She told us a room on the 8th floor in the West Wing was available. This further angered me because the 8th floor room should have been offered in the first place to accommodate our previous request. Rachel apologized and said that a bellman would be up to escort us to our new room within 10-15 minutes. While we waited for the bellman to arrive another guest opened our door and entered the room. He said; “This is my room”. He left and went back to the desk. The front desk had already re-assigned the room and given out a key before verifying we had been moved. This also tells me that housekeeping is not required to inspect rooms between guests that are being moved if necessary. The bell staff called before bringing the new room keys to get our luggage claim number. Hohns was the bellman who delivered our luggage and brought the keys. He escorted us to the new room. When we arrived the door was ajar and the deadbolt locked out to keep the door open. Hohns opened the door and proceeded into the room. Once inside we noticed there was a bathroom scale sitting on the chair in the room. The bed had been made and the room looked clean at first glance. Once again I looked out the window as that was the reason for moving. Again, it was of a wall although if you looked up you could see other buildings on the Strip. At this point we were ready to give up on having a decent view, we were very tired and ready to settle and get on with vacation. Hohns unloaded the luggage and we tipped him and sent him on his way. Because I was so preoccupied with the view I hadn’t looked at the bathroom before Hohns left which was a huge mistake. When I opened the water closet there were no towels on the shelf, a hanger left by a previous guest, the toilet paper was hanging down to the floor. Then I opened the shower to find it still dirty as well with water sitting in the floor. No amenities such as soap, shampoo, bath gel had been placed in the room. We had been moved to a dirty room. Now I am absolutely furious.I called the front desk and asked to speak with a manager. After holding for 10 minutes, and I did watch the clock, I hung up the phone and had to call back. Ambrosia was the name of the lady who took this call. She wanted to know what the call was in reference to rather than immediately putting a manager on the phone. I went through the entire situation with her once again and asked if she would be able to help me otherwise direct me to a manager. Ambrosia placed me on hold only to come back and say that they could move us to another room and offer nothing else. Ambrosia’s tone was dismissive considering the very valid complaints that I had provided. She also did not apologize for the problems so I asked to speak with her manager. Airdell was the supervisor/manager who then took the call. He said that he had been listening to the conversation with Ambrosia and that she was correct in that nothing could be done at that time other than moving us to another room. They also couldn’t guarantee the room was going to have a better view. Airdell said that if we wanted a room with a better view we could call the desk Sunday morning to be moved. Once we unpacked moving was NOT an option. Both Airdell and Ambrosia basically skirted all the other problems and offered no apology. They did however blame the housekeeping department for turning in a dirty room as clean for a guest arrival. By this time it was around 4:30pm, two and half hours wasted. We were all together exhausted with dealing with the hotel staff, reservation and room issues. I told Airdell to get us into a clean room no matter what the view. He told me that we were going to be moved to another room on the same floor. Before he hung the phone up I could hear the room number we were being assigned and immediately went down the hall to 8515. We moved our luggage ourselves and stood in the hallway waiting for the keys to arrive. After about 10 minutes standing in the hallway a suited member of the staff approached us without introducing himself although it was clear he was bringing the keys to the new room. He asked for our identification which I appreciated for security. The gentleman did not offer any apology on behalf of the hotel or escort us into the new room. He simply handed us the keys and walked away. No more than “May I see your ID” was uttered from his mouth without even addressing us by name. Once inside room 8515 I immediately investigated the entire room and the view. The room was clean and the view although not ideal was much much better. We could see the desert in the background as well as the Luxor, Mandalay Bay, Excalibur and if you looked to the hard right the Statue of Liberty at New York, New York. All of this was across the roof of some part of MGM. This final room although clean and with a better view did have a problem. The security latch on the inside of the room was broken. The only way to lock the door was by deadbolt. At this point were so thoroughly disenchanted that the lock being broken was almost comical. Of course I did NOT call the desk because none of the other calls resulted in any major response from the management. We simply went on with our 3 day vacation. Our situation speaks volumes about the MGM Grand and the manner in which they handle guests. It just so happens that on the day after we returned home I was watching a show called “Extreme Megastructures” and wouldn’t you know that MGM Grand was one of those structures. With thousands of rooms this behemoth property is a revolving door of guests and it seems that unless you are a VIP or high-roller you are just another number that can be forgotten or overlooked. As a manager of a luxury hotel in my hometown I understand the way guests should be treated and the way problems should be dealt with to put guests at ease. MGM does not deserve its AAA Four Diamond rating if my experience is similar to others. My suggestion is to book a room elsewhere!!!!	
Sep 18 2009 	Biggest hotel in Vegas no denying that one...good stay!	Ok, so I stayed at the MGM Grand in the middle of August 2009 for 4 nights. We were in the Grand Tower (we turned down the upgrade as we knew these rooms would be bigger and give us more space), I stayed on the 15th floor, didn't have a view of the strip but that didn't really matter.The hotel itself is vast...in fact that word doesn't even cover it! As other people have said, it takes ages to get out to the strip but that is the same with most of the hotels as they are set back from the strip itself.The room was big, comfortable and had air-conditioning, which was much needed in the 105 degree dry heat! There are a huge number of restaurants and bars as well as the lion enclosure (although don't get me started on that)...and the casino is MASSIVE...my sister one $160 on her second draw of a slot machine, on her 30th BD (albeit at 4am with jetlag!)...We ate at the Sushi restaurant one night, it was AMAZING. Expect to pay around $50 per person for most evening meals with drinks. That same night we saw &quot;KA&quot; the Cirque Du Soleil which plays at the theatre in the MGM. As guests we got 40% off the ticket which meant that we could get really really good seats for about $80 each. The show was out of this world. I've been lucky enough to see 4 of the Cirque Du Soleil productions at the Royal Albert Hall in London but nothing beats seeing it in its home venue. The staging was definitely the star of the show, it will have you gasping in amazement at how much it adapts and moves.The main trip we did was the Helicopter trip over the GrandCanyon and I would say it is well worth the money. The views were amazing and the trip didn't end up taking a whole day which is good when time is short!I think next time I go to Vegas I'll definitely stay a bit further up the strip as MGM is at the bottom, and hey, if I win the lotto I'll be at the Bellagio!	
