Sep 13 2009 	Great fun...good value	We visited Vegas on a 4 night/5 day schedule at MGM Grand. We had read all the MGM negatives on Trip Advisor prior to the trip -- and thought most of the criticisms nit picky (rooms too &quot;old&quot;; plumbing that could be heard now and then; room door too far from elevator, etc. etc.)My oh my. How spoiled some folks have become as travelers. We had a great time here overall -- and for a fair price. Summary tips on how to have a great visit, in our opinion, to Vegas and MGM: Consider going 4 nights instead of the standard 3. (5 nights would have been too much. Like 5 helpings of your favorite sundae. Too much of a fun thing.) 4 nights takes the rush-rush out of a Vegas visit. We felt we had all day and night every day. Just the right amount of visit time.Rent a car. It allows you maximum mobility and freedom to go off the strip -- hopefully to sites and casinos that will save you money compared to the Strip destinations for food, casinos, etc. We rented a Mustang convertible (it was our 25th anniversary), and found cruising the Strip and adjacent-to-strip thoroughfares a most memorable experience. Las Vegas, after all, is candy for the eyes at night. MGM: Expansive, yes. But not so big that a 5 minutes walk from front desk to pool or casino will ruin one's stay. (Many critics here said as much in their posts. Sorry, but I disagree. And we're both 63.) We stayed in an 18th floor room in the Grand Tower. KIng bed. (Yes, the beds are the most comfortable we've experienced. Why can't we buy a bed as comfortable in the stores at home??)We brought our own alcohol (one bottle will do.) We purchased water -- two bottles -- off the Strip for a dollar. We refilled the bottles in our room and kept the ice bucket replenished (on principle I will not pay MGM prices for a bottle of water.) The pool: a most relaxing experience. The Lazy River especially. (The tubes @ $16 each not so bad...especially if you &quot;sell&quot; yours at half-price to another guest when you leave the pool area. One couple offered us $20 for ours and we took it.) Gambling: not much variety in the MGM machines...and they did run tight. (Why doesn't a casino like MGM loosen the strings a bit, returning to a time 10 years ago when the sound of WINNERS at the slots were a best advertisement? Nowadays, the &quot;sound&quot; of people getitng hammered by the bandits over and over and over again. We are not, by the way, table game players.) Not much better luck off the strip, by the way. All in all, we had best gambling fun and luck at Texas Station (off strip...a car ride), Palazzo/Venetian...and NYNY.MGM Staff: All helpful and cooperative. Attractions:Liberace Museum. He was from Milwaukee and so are we. Worth the $15 admission.Down Tropicana about 5 mins in the car. Larry Jones, &quot;Impersonator&quot; -- at the Royal Resort off the strip about a block. OK entertainment. He bills himself as an impersonator. In fact, he does parody. If you dont go expecting a Frank Caliendo experiende, it is a fun night out for about $40. He obviously loves his work. Tix store -- all along the strip. They are not half price off -- more like 30%. But a good savings. Food: plenty of options at MGM...including a food court that is easy to find. Just avoid for breakfast on Thursday and Friday. Convention crowds. (Suggest you scope out the entire first floor when yoiu first arrive, so there will be no surprises at the end of your visit. One poster here did not discover the food court til the final hours of their visit...and presumably paid a premium for basic breakfast and lunch) The Buffet: we did dinner one night. Not memorable.I guess that sums it up from our perspective. By the way, we spent about $2500 total -- $700 of that gambling losses. Subtract the gambling and convertible rental, and it's a $1300 memory. Hey...it's Vegas. One-of-a-kind fun and decadence on a 24/7 platter. Enjoy.	
