Sep 3 2009 	Get the PRIMA	We were offered the PRIMA card. You don’t PAY anything, but rather you place a $500 credit towards your room for you to spend. This can be spent anywhere within the hotel and also within the other MGM hotels (mirage, luxor, etc). Basically you’re telling MGM you will spend at least $500 at THEIR hotel.In exchange for this, they give you free, VIP, front of the line access to: Studio 54, Tabu, and Wet Republic (21+ pool that is like a club complete with DJ, drinks, private cabanas, and plenty of people watching). They also give you 2 for 1 drinks at the bars, 2 for 1 entrees at the fancy restaurants, and they let you go to the front of the taxi line. AND, we were upgraded to a celebrity spa suite. The hotel was nice. Great room, great pool options (with lazy river), great restaurants. Only bad thing is it’s a big away from all the hotels.	
Sep 3 2009 	pleasantly surprised but expectations were low	When I make my own reservations for Vegas, I always Hotwire a five star hotel, and usually get the Venetian which I am very happy with. So I was a little worried when my friend booked the MGM. It isn't one of the newer hotels anymore and the thing about Vegas hotels is that they get shabby quickly if they aren't taken care of. So I was pleasantly surprised that our room was quite clean, fresh feeling, and with all the amenities I would have asked for. Once inside it didn't feel much different in layout or design than, say, the Four Seasons Las Vegas, which I stayed at last year (of course the bathroom was much less posh than at the Four Seasons or Venetian). Anyway I found the room perfectly adequate, and the long walks aren't any different than any other casino hotels. The monorail station is great if you're planning to go far up the Strip.	
