Aug 24 2009 	Fabulous girls only trip	I'm really not quite sure why people could ever have a problem with this hotel. Perhaps because it was my first trip to Vegas and I have nothing to compare it to I was more impressed, but I found the accommodations and service to be outstanding. I'll break up my review to make it more organized.Location: MGM is so close to the airport (about a 10 minute drive) so that was nice. It is on one end of the strip so you have to go up if you want to see the rest. I could have dealt with staying somewhere more centrally located, but we did walk from the Belaggio back home one night after several cocktails and it wasn't that bad. Plus there is an overpass that takes you to NYNY. We spent a lot of time over there because it seemed like more of a party atmosphere. Check-in: We arrived at around 1pm and had no problems checking in early. We did not have to wait on line at all. I asked for a Grand Tower room (as opposed to West Wing) and was granted one. All of our &quot;extras&quot; were explained to us and we were sent on our way.Room: The room was very clean and spacious for three girls. The bathroom was large and spotless. The beds were extremely comfortable. We had a smoking room and I didn't feel the room had an overly present odor of smoke. We didn't have our room cleaned while we were there because we had stuff all over the place. We just kept our &quot;do not disturb&quot; sign on and made our own beds. Our view was amazing. I realize that some rooms are on the airport side, but not ours! We had a clear view of NYNY, Excalibur, and the Luxor. It was gorgeous at night. Staff: The staff here is awesome. It's like everyone is in a good mood and always willing to help. From the bartenders to the cocktail waitresses, they really want you to feel welcome. Our first drink down at the lobby bar we talked with MGM's beverage director and a couple of the bartenders. They gave us the low down on where to go and when. Our cocktail waitress by the nickel slots was so sweet. Also, the servers in the buffet were on top of everything and also cordial. Everyone was willing to answer questions and always with a smile. If only all hotels had staff as good as these...Buffet: The deal I booked had our meals included 3 times a day if we wished. We never used it that much but many days we did have breakfast and lunch there. The food was good. Nothing to write home about, but there was a good variety and the quality was sufficient. The short ribs were amazing I must say. The only suggestion I would have for the buffet is to change it up a bit. There were the exact same items available for all 5 days we were there. It did get a little boring. The service was great and even though there were really long lines to get in at times, they have a great system that gets you seated and eating pretty quickly. I was glad to have had this option and it saved us a ton of money. Ka: This is one area where I can't give 5 stars. Of course, this is at no fault to the MGM, but I just felt a little ripped off by this show. Perhaps I am used to Broadway productions in NY, but I just felt slighted. I thought Vegas shows were supposed to be the most amazing in the world. I watched a girl twirl a baton for 20 minutes and people pretend to fight. There were a few high points, but I would recommend trying a different show. Craftsteak: We decided to eat at Craft on Saturday evening after seeing Ka. We were promptly seated since we had a reservation. However, the hostess put us in the front of the restaurant almost in the hallway where all of the hotel guests and visitors were passing by. We asked if there was a table further in the restaurant and after initially being refused were moved. That was a good thing because the restaurant is beautiful and with the prices, I wanted to feel the ambiance. This was one of the best meals I have ever had and I highly recommend it if you can spring for it. Pool: We went to the adult pool on the days we did go out. We had no interest in Wet Republic so I couldn't say if it is fun or worth it. The adult pool was nice and relaxing. No kids splashing around, just grown ups sitting in the water reading or drinking giant yard frozen drinks. The pool is very far from everything else though. This is not a complaint, just information. If you want to get from the pool to the buffet it is about a 15-20 walk through the casino. Gambling: We only played slots here. My friend won $40 on the nickels our first day. I had better luck at Excalibur and then downtown Vegas with penny slots. Studio 54: We tried to go one night but it was after 4 am so it was closed. Oops. Taxis: Get in the line for a taxi and please please tip the attendant. I couldn't believe how many people didn't just pull out a couple of bucks to give the poor guy who stands out there all day in the heat. Check-out: Totally quick and easy. All of the perks we had gotten were taken off the bill and I still can't believe how economical the accommodations were.Like I said, this was my first trip to Vegas. I did walk around and see many of the other hotels though and for the deal we got, I wouldn't have wanted to stay anywhere else.	
Aug 24 2009 	Amazing!	When me and my partner booked to stay at the MGM Grand, we read the reviews and recieved mixed views on the hotel, now after going and getting back all i can say is that i would recommend this hotel to everyone. The MGM is only 5 mins drive away from the airport, we flew from Manchester UK so it was a long flight and we were really happy about the fact that we could get to the hotel quite quickly, when we got there the ques for check in took about 15 mins, we slid the assistant 20 dollars and got our room upgraded to a better room with a strip view which was mint! The room was excellent, the bed was like a cloud...only bigger and more comfortable! everytime i lay on it i passed out because it was that good! The room was cleaned everyday, with fresh towels and bedding. The whole hotel is huge! it takes a while to get your bearings when you leave your room, because there are so many different walkways around the casino and restaraunts ETC. We ate breakfast at the Rainforest Cafe most days, which was really nice with reasonable prices, the only downside was a gut who worked there called Jimmy who insisted on telling us and everyone where to go and what to do while we were in Vegas, he was annoying to say the least! We went to see the Cirque du Soloeil show (KA) which is situated inside the MGM, and i can honestly say that it was the best show EVER!!!! Definately worth every penny for the tickets, it was awesome! just a shame you couldnt take photos inside. The pool was nice although we didnt go much because we were too busy exploring everywhere.There is a monorail station connected to the hotel which is the best way to get up and down the strip, 13 dollars for 24 hours, we used it several times a day, it stops at almost every hotel and its way cheaper than getting a taxi. The staff were very friendly all through the hotel, always happy to direct you where to go when we got lost. Overall the hotel was brilliant, im already planning our next holiday there and i only got back 2 days ago! i hope this helps everyone.	
Aug 23 2009 	Average Strip Hotel	I spent three days in Vegas as part of a larger trip. I hadnt stayed at the MGM for many years, but we were looking for a cheap stay and they had a great deal on bungalow suites - $120ish a night - so for that price i thought why not.The room was a great size although a bit shabby. There was a mini-bar with nothing inside it - which was annoying since it is always so far to go down to the casino for a drink late at night. I certainly wouldnt be paying much more for the room than what i did. The bed was huge and comfortable. The bed linen was suprisingly decent - and had obviously been refreshed more recently than the hotel room itself!! The bathroom was acceptable but also in need of a refurb, the towels were average.Wireless internet access is charged on a daily basis which i think is a bit tight - in this day and age it should be complimentary.The hotel is basically straight down the middle in terms of quality, a standard strip hotel - no more no less. Casino is fine, restaurants, pool etc are fine. Its not going to set the world on fire, but then at the price i was paying who cares.Unfortunately the location these days leaves a lot to be desired. Usually i stay up at the bellagio junction which is much more convenient for shopping, eating and nightlife. The MGM is just a bit too far away from the action.	
Aug 23 2009 	I would stay somewhere else next time	I already submitted a post for this but didn't realize I could not edit it later so I am redoing it and completing it in its entirely.  We were scheduled to stay from a Tuesday through Saturday but arrived a day earlier. Initially customer service was great. They went out of their way to move us from our basic room that we had the first unscheduled night to the Marquis Suite we had originally reserved by allowing us late check out from one room and early check in to our Marquis SuiteAs other people have pointed out, the hotel rooms are dated for the most part. We had a 1500 square foot Marquis 'suite' and it has three 27 inch tube tvs. The marble bar in the room is filthy as my wife has pointed out. Some of the wall paper is peeling. There is a small fridge in the marquis suite but no fridge in the basic room.The furnishings and paintings are definitely from the 80's with brass trim around the bathroom shower doors and closet doors.The bed in the standard room with two queen beds was terrible. The sheets were hard, scratchy and uncomfortable. The bed dipped in the middle and caused sleeping problems for me.The biggest complaint I had is the air conditioning. It has been noted by several people here. It did not cool down enough in the basic room we had last night. We lived with it. There was one unit in the basic room. In the marquis suite there are 4 units. The suite is large and there are windows pretty much continuously from one end to the other Probably 80 feet of windows about 5 feet high. They allow a huge amount of heat from the sun in the room. The 4 units, do not provide enough cooling power. I should say that 3 units do not provide enough power since the one in our bedroom doesn't work. I have made three phone calls in the past 5 hours and the only that has been done is that a low level maintenance guy came out to replace a filter that was essentially new and didn't need changing. They offered to move us to another room but we have already settled in and don't wish to move again. I just want them to fix the damn air conditioner. We are getting towards the end of a two week trip.The drain in our sink in the basic room was very slow and made gurgling noises.The walk from the room to the pool was only about 5 minutes as well as to the buffet. I will update this later to reflect other aspects of the hotel. Right now the room is an issue for me.Internet is $450.00 a month at $15 a day.The following happened after I submitted the above..................I finally decided that I could not handle the a/c not working in the bedroom. I called a few more times and got really irritated with the facilities people and the front desk managers that kept passing the buck. Around 10pm the first night in the Marquis Suite I agreed to be moved to another suite and requested to talk to the hotel manager. He was not available but they said he would call me. They had somebody come up with keys to a different Marquis suite. The new Marquis Suite had just been completely remodeled and from what I was told, it was an experimental design and it was the only one like it in the entire hotel. I had no idea of what to expect. I will briefly describe the room here even though there is only one of them. The layout is essentially the same as the Marquis Suite shown on the MGM site except for the fact that there are two 50 inch lcd's in the front room with seating for 8. The dining table sat 5. There was a pool table in the front room with another 42 inch lcd next to that. Each of the two bedrooms had a 42 inch lcd tv. Each of the two master bathrooms had tv's behind the mirror. Everything was new. The shower in each bathroom was so large that each end of the shower had a separate large rainfall shower head with hand held shower nozzle for the hard to reach areas. In one bathroom there was also a jetted tub with LED lights. There was stainless steel trim around the doors and everything was contemporary. The remotes for the tv were touch screen and also controlled the electric drapes/shears/lights. The a/c thermostats were all digital. All the carpeting, flooring, drapes, sinks, counters, etc were different and new. It didn't resemble the old Marquis Suite at all except for the outline of the room. One complaint I read on here was about the drunk people being noisy in the hallway or their rooms. The walls are thin here and people in their rooms are easily heard as you walk by their door in the hallway. We had some kids running up and down the hallway and our last night, 4 young guys were trying to get their key card to work on our door. I was watching them via the peep hole and they eventually went away. I think they thought they were on a different floor. The Marquis Suites are on the end and have concrete walls so there was no noise from other rooms transferring to our room. The floors and ceiling are concrete also so it was pretty quiet all around. Oddly enough, the new updated suite still had some of the plumbing problems noted by others and experienced by me in the previous Marquis Suite that was not updated. When the tub drained or the sinks drained, there were a series of gurgling noises coming from the shower drain and vice versa. The other thing is that the a/c units in the new unit still used the old old a/c unit except they were retrofitted with digital displays. They worked better than the a/c units in the old Suite but they still sucked as far as I am concerned. The a/c unit in our Disney hotel would get down to 66 easily. The one in our bedroom got down to about 73 and the front room ones got down to about 74: they could not get any lower at any time day or night. This is too warm for me. When I sleep I like it to be in the upper 60's. My home a/c does this with no problem. The rest of the room was so great we did not complain a second time. The unit in the other bedroom did get down to about 67. Maintenance here is not up to par.The hotel food court had a poor selection. There was a fat Tuesday's, a pretzel place, a Hagen Daz, McDonald's, Mama ilardos pizza, Nathans hot dogs, and a Panda Express type of place. The other places were sit down which I did not visit. I felt the selection was very poor after going to a place like New York New York across the street. We had a deal where we got the buffet for free during our stay. I would give the buffet a 5 out of ten if I were in a generous mood. The lines ranged from 5 minutes to about 25 minutes. There were plenty of tables to seat us at but they insisted on making us stand and wait in line for our tables. It is obvious they didn't hire enough people to bus the tables promptly and only half of the steam pans were being used. They could have easily had everybody sit down quickly but management is lacking here. It was pretty disorganized. In order to get any butter for the rolls, you had to ask your individual server to get it for you. To get anything to drink you also have to wait for the server to take your order and bring it to you. I guess this is their way of trying to get tips out of you even though you get your own food. The food quality and selection was sub par. I say this after having eaten at the Carnival buffet at the Rio Hotel during my same trip. The Rio had about ten times as many items, is much larger and actually a few dollars cheaper. The MGM buffet would get one star out of ten compared to the Rio buffet. Even with the buffet being free for us, we found ourselves tired of it after the second day. We paid to eat elsewhere such as the close by Subway, Wendy's, Del Taco, McDonald's, etc. The MGM buffet doesn't even compete with the local Indian owned casino by my house.I used the valet a few times during our stay. We had to wait less than ten minutes for our car and on the last day I discovered that you can call down to valet and have the car brought up so it is ready as soon as you get downstairs. This worked well.The pools seemed ok. I only went once. They were pretty much empty in the morning but certainly filled up quickly. We could see a few pools from our Suite. There are 5 pools. They have an adult area called Wet Republic that charges admission. I did not go in there but the moo moo's I saw going in there certainly were not any motivation for me to pay and see them in a two piece.Check in was quick and we did automated check out via the tv. Our bill appeared to be correct.There seemed to be too much smoke in here and I suspect maintenance is an issue in this area also. Our twelve year old found the smoke offensive and made it clear to us he didn't like it.If I got the same updated suite with a great deal again I would stay at the MGM again but they don't guarantee a particular room and if there is only one of the type of room I stayed in, then I would hate to be stuck at the check in desk getting a different crappy room. They have to update all of their rooms and the hotel can use a major renovation. Maybe they should just bulldoze it. It is long in the tooth to say the least and I suspect they are funneling all their money into their City Center project across the street. Any hotel still using tube tv's is pretty much a motel six in my book.I am not a big traveler but I have stayed at the Palazzo, Venetian, Disney Grand Californian, Luxor, Woodway in Vancouver BC, and various other less grand hotels.	
